   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b0bd5b7a-c99a-4428-9709-cb6335da1cd9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Index Base and Slice Bounds Rationale"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "74e7d00b-19eb-4213-9c37-e0da5a702527",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Valid Questions\n",
    "\n",
    "Why does sequence indexing start at 0 and not i?\n",
    "Why does a sequence slice s[i:j] include s[i] but excludes s[j]?\n",
    "\n",
    "Not an arbitrary choice -> rational and practical reasons for these questions\n",
    "\n",
    "We want to determine how we should handle sequneces of consecutive integers\n",
    "-> represent positions of elements in a sequence\n",
    "\n",
    "['a', 'b', 'c', 'd']\n",
    "      1 2 3 4\n",
    "      0 1 2 3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "6e67646b-3bcf-4d97-8ebf-4354b85478ee",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Slice Bounds\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider following sequence of integers\n",
    "1, 2, 3, ..., 15\n",
    "\n",
    "How can we describe the range of numbers without using an ellipses (...)?\n",
    "\n",
    "a) 1 <= n <= 15\n",
    "b) 0 < n <= 15\n",
    "c) 1 <= n < 16\n",
    "d) 0 < n < 16\n",
    "\n",
    "(b) and (d) can become odd at times\n",
    "Suppose we want to describe unsigned integers 0, 1, 2, ..., 10\n",
    "Using (b) or (d) we would nee dto use a signed integer for the lower bound\n",
    "b) -1 < n <= 10\n",
    "c) -1 < n < 11\n",
    "TOSS THESE\n",
    "\n",
    "Now consider this sequence: 2, 3, ..., 16\n",
    "\n",
    "a) 2 <= n <= 16\n",
    "c) 2 <= n < 17\n",
    "\n",
    "How many elements in sequence? 15\n",
    "Calculting number of elements\n",
    "\n",
    "a) 15 = 16 - 2 + 1 # = upper - lower + 1\n",
    "c) 15 = 17 - 2 = upper - lower\n",
    "\n",
    "So (c) seems simpler for that calculation\n",
    "We will get to a second reason in a bit but now use (c)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "9e4f0828-3863-4dc0-b6bb-4412d0b2ac9b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Starting Indexing at 0 instead of 1\n",
    "\n",
    "When we count elements we natually start counting at 1 so why 0?\n",
    "Consider the following\n",
    "\n",
    "2, 3, ..., 16 sequence length = 15\n",
    "index n (1 based)\n",
    "1, 2, 3, ..., 15  1 <= n < 16, upper bound = length + 1\n",
    "index n (0 based)\n",
    "0, 1, 2, ..., 14  0 <= n < 15, upper bound = length\n",
    "\n",
    "For any sequence s, the index range is given by:\n",
    "0 based: 0 <= n < len(s)\n",
    "1 based: 1 <= n < len(s) + 1\n",
    "\n",
    "So, 0 based appears simpler"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "652925fe-d216-4e66-a544-00ff6f09095d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Another reason for choosing 0 based indexing\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider this sequence:\n",
    "a, b, c, d, ..., z\n",
    "1, 2, 3, 4, ..., 26 (1 based)\n",
    "0, 1, 2, 3, ..., 25 (0 based)\n",
    "\n",
    "How many elements come before d? 3 elements\n",
    "1 based, index(d) -> 4, 4 - 1 elements\n",
    "0 based, index(d) -> 3, 3 elements\n",
    "\n",
    "So using 0 based indexing the number of elements that precede the index is the index itself!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "87c6d661-7056-4674-a561-a4aa80e244e8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "Choosing 0 based indexing for sequences\n",
    "Describing ranges of indices using range(l, u) -> l <= n < u\n",
    "\n",
    "We have the following results\n",
    "The indicies of any sequence s are given by: range(0, len(s)) [0 <= n < len(s)]\n",
    "First index: 0, last index: len(s) - 1\n",
    "Number of indeices before index n: n\n",
    "The length of a range(l, u) is given by: l - u\n",
    "\n",
    "s = [a, b, c, ..., z]\n",
    "     0, 1, 2, ..., 25\n",
    "\n",
    "len(s) -> 26\n",
    "indices -> range(0, 26)\n",
    "n elements that precede s[n]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "9181ca99-d4e3-4173-95b3-8b00cf9db170",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Slicing \n",
    "\n",
    "Because of convention on starting indexing at 0 and defiuning ranges using [lower, upper) \n",
    "We can think in these terms:\n",
    "Each item in a sequence is like a box with indices between the boxes\n",
    "\n",
    " a b c d e f\n",
    "0 1 2 3 4 5 6\n",
    "\n",
    "6 is length of the sequence\n",
    "s[2:4] -> [c, d] numbers between 2 and 4 (i.e. c, d)\n",
    "first 2 elements: s[0:2] = s[:2]\n",
    "everything else: s[2:6] = s[2:]\n",
    "In general we can split a sequence into two with k elements in the first sequence s[:k] s[k:]"
   ]
  },
